meta_authors:
Darby, H
Kelly, F
Elmualim, A
meta_title: Whole life carbon  a building case study
bldg_construction_method:
main warehouse: steel portal frame with insulated metal deck roof
office: steel composite frame with composite  concrete slab roof
mass concrete pad foundations
cladding: precast concrete insulated sandwich panels
lca_goal_scope:
This paper describes a case study on the whole life carbon cycle of a warehouse building in Swindon, UK.
It examines the relationship between embodied carbon (Ec) and operational carbon (Oc), the proportions of Ec from the structural and non-structural elements,carbonbenchmarkingofthe structure, the value of cradle to site or cradle to grave assessments and the significance of the timing of emissions during the life of the building.

meta_title: Carbon Reduction Measures-Based LCA of Prefabricated Temporary Housing with Renewable Energy Systems
lca_goal_scope: "In order to assess the environmental impacts of prefabricated temporary housing equipped with renewable energy systems, this study first divides the life cycle of temporary housing into six stages, and then establishes a life cycle assessment (LCA) model for each stage. meta_title: A multi-scale life-cycle energy and greenhouse-gas emissions analysis model for residential buildings
lca_goal_scope:
This study presents a holistic model and software tool which take into account energy requirements
at the building scale, i.e. the embodied and operational energy of the building and its refurbishment, and at the urban scale,
i.e. the embodied energy of nearby infrastructures (roads, power lines, etc.) and the transport energy (direct and indirect) of
its occupants. All associated greenhouse-gas emissions are also quantified. A case study, located near Melbourne, Australia,
confirms that each of the embodied, operational and transport requirements is nearly equally significant.

meta_title: Benchmarks for environmental impact of housing in Europe: De nition of archetypes and LCA of the residential building stock
lca_goal_scope:
This study describes the results of Life Cycle Assessment (LCA) applied to 24 statistically-based dwelling archetypes,
representative of the EU housing stock in 2010. The aim is to quantify the average environmental
impacts related to housing in Europe and to define reference values (baseline scenario) for policies development

meta_title: Calculation of a building's life cycle carbon emissions based on Ecotect and building information modeling
lca_goal_scope: The life cycle energy consumption and CO2 emissions of a university building in the midwest have been calculated using Ecotect and BIM models (Wang et al., 2011; Basbagill et al., 2013). The study compared the life cycle performance of various design configurations (in terms of CO2 emissions and energy consumption) and their distributions over the stages of the building's lifetime.
